  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "XXV.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "THE GIFTS WHICH MIGHT BE GIVEN FOR THE TABERNACLE AND THE PRIESTS’ DRESSES.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2) Speak unto the children of Israel that they bring me an offering.—God, being about to command the construction of a dwelling for Himself, such as the circumstances of the case allowed, prefaced His directions concerning its materials and form by instructing Moses to invite the people to contribute from their stores, as an offering to Himself, the various substances which were suitable for the dwelling and its appurtenances. The erection of sanctuaries is one of the fittest occasions for man to shew his gratitude to God by giving to Him of His own, largely and liberally.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(2) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Speak unto the children of Israel that they ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "bring ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "me an offering.—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "God, being about to command the construction of a dwelling for Himself, such as the circumstances of the case allowed, prefaced His directions concerning its materials and form by instructing Moses to invite the people to contribute from their stores, as an offering to Himself, the various substances which were suitable for the dwelling and its appurtenances. The erection of sanctuaries is one of the fittest occasions for man to shew his gratitude to God by giving to Him of His own, largely and liberally.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of every man that giveth it willingly with his heart.—Heb., of every man whose heart impels him. Unless gifts come from the heart, they are an offence to God. He “loveth a cheerful giver.” When the time came, a noble and liberal spirit was not wanting. (See Exodus 35:21-29; Exodus 36:3-7.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Of every man that giveth it willingly with his heart.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Heb., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "of every man whose heart impels him. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Unless gifts come from the heart, they are an offence to God. He “loveth a cheerful giver.” When the time came, a noble and liberal spirit was not wanting. (See ",
