        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Speak unto the children of Israel that they bring me an offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word translated \"offering\" is that commonly rendered\" heave-offering;\" but it seems to be used here (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 30:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 35:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) in a generic sense. The propriety of the people, when God was about establishing his habitation among them, presenting to God all the materials needed, is self-evident and requires no comment. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Of every man that giveth it willingly",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally, \"of every man whose heart drives him.\" God will have no gifts but such as are freely offered. He \"loveth a cheerful giver. If a man gives grudgingly or of necessity,\" God rejects the gift. On the noble spirit which the people showed when the appeal was made to them, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 35:21-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 36:3",
        "children": []
      },
